region isn't available for read or <br>write access unless there's a failover to the secondary region. If the <br>primary region becomes unavailable, you can choose to fail over to the <br>secondary region. After the failover has completed, the secondary region<br> becomes the primary region, and you can again read and write data.</div><div align="left">Because data is replicated to the secondary region asynchronously, a <br/>failure that affects the primary region may result in data loss if the <br/>primary region can't be recovered. The interval between the most recent <br/>writes to the primary region and the last write to the secondary region <br/>is known as the recovery point objective (RPO). The RPO indicates the <br/>point in time to which data can be recovered. Azure Storage typically <br/>has an RPO of less than 15 minutes, although there's currently no SLA on<br/> how long it takes to replicate data to the secondary region.</div>" for at least 30 days (for example, invoices for your customers).</li><li><strong>Cold access tier</strong>: Optimized for storing data that is infrequently accessed and stored for at least 90 days.</li><li><strong>Archive access tier</strong>: Appropriate for data that is <br>rarely accessed and stored for at least 180 days, with flexible latency <br>requirements (for example, long-term The archive access tier isn't available at the account level.</li><li>Hot, cool, cold, and archive tiers can be set at the blob level, during or after upload.</li><li>Data in the cool and cold access tiers can tolerate slightly lower <br/>availability, but still requires high durability, retrieval latency, and<br/> throughput characteristics similar to hot data. For cool and cold data,<br/> a lower availability service-level agreement (SLA) and higher access <br/>costs compared to hot data are acceptable trade-offs for lower storage <br/>costs.</li><li>Archive storage stores data offline and offers the lowest storage <br/>costs, but also the highest costs to rehydrate and access data.</li><br></ul>" Once you install Azure<br/> File Sync on your local Windows server, it will automatically stay <br/>bi-directionally synced with your files in Azure.</p><br/><p>With Azure File Sync, you can:</p><br/><ul><li>Use any protocol that's available on Windows Server to access your data locally, including SMB, NFS, and FTPS.</li><li>Have as many caches as you need across the world.</li><li>Replace a failed local server by installing Azure File Sync on a new server in the same datacenter.</li><li>Configure cloud tiering so the most frequently accessed files are <br/>replicated locally, while infrequently accessed files are kept in the <br/>cloud until requested.</li></ul>" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontFamily=Helvetica;fontSize=11;fontColor=default;labelBackgroundColor=default;" vertex="1" parent="1"> <mxGeometry x="-9.5" y="309" width="247" height="271" as="geometry" /> </mxCell> </root> </mxGraphModel> </diagram> </mxfile>

div.div:
By default, data in the secondary region isn't available for read or
write access unless there's a failover to the secondary region. If the
primary region becomes unavailable, you can choose to fail over to the
secondary region. After the failover has completed, the secondary region
becomes the primary region, and you can again read and write data.

Because data is replicated to the secondary region asynchronously, a
failure that affects the primary region may result in data loss if the
primary region can't be recovered. The interval between the most recent
writes to the primary region and the last write to the secondary region
is known as the recovery point objective (RPO). The RPO indicates the
point in time to which data can be recovered. Azure Storage typically
has an RPO of less than 15 minutes, although there's currently no SLA on
how long it takes to replicate data to the secondary region.

ul.li: Hot access tier: Optimized for storing data that is accessed frequently (for example, images for your website).
Cool access tier: Optimized for data that is infrequently accessed and stored for at least 30 days (for example, invoices for your customers).
Cold access tier: Optimized for storing data that is infrequently accessed and stored for at least 90 days.

Archive access tier: Appropriate for data that is
rarely accessed and stored for at least 180 days, with flexible latency
requirements (for example, long-term backups)
imp
Hot, cool, and cold access tiers can be set at the account level. The archive access tier isn't available at the account level.
Hot, cool, cold, and archive tiers can be set at the blob level, during or after upload.

Data in the cool and cold access tiers can tolerate slightly lower
availability, but still requires high durability, retrieval latency, and
throughput characteristics similar to hot data. For cool and cold data,
a lower availability service-level agreement (SLA) and higher access
costs compared to hot data are acceptable trade-offs for lower storage
costs.

Archive storage stores data offline and offers the lowest storage
costs, but also the highest costs to rehydrate and access data.

div.div:
AzCopy is a command-line utility that you can use to copy blobs or files
to or from your storage account. With AzCopy, you can upload files,
download files, copy files between storage accounts, and even
synchronize files. AzCopy can even be configured to work with other
cloud providers to help move files back and forth between clouds.
Synchronizing blobs or files with AzCopy is one-direction
synchronization. When you synchronize, you designated the source and
destination, and AzCopy will copy files or blobs in that direction. It
doesn't synchronize bi-directionally based on timestamps or other
metadata.

div.p:
Azure Storage Explorer is a standalone app that provides a graphical
interface to manage files and blobs in your Azure Storage Account. It
works on Windows, macOS, and Linux operating systems and uses AzCopy on
the backend to perform all of the file and blob management tasks. With
Storage Explorer, you can upload to Azure, download from Azure, or move
between storage accounts.

div.p:
Azure File Sync is a tool that lets you centralize your file shares
in Azure Files and keep the flexibility, performance, and compatibility
of a Windows file server. It’s almost like turning your Windows file
server into a miniature content delivery network. Once you install Azure
File Sync on your local Windows server, it will automatically stay
bi-directionally synced with your files in Azure.
With Azure File Sync, you can:

ul.li: Use any protocol that's available on Windows Server to access your data locally, including SMB, NFS, and FTPS.
Have as many caches as you need across the world.
Replace a failed local server by installing Azure File Sync on a new server in the same datacenter.

Configure cloud tiering so the most frequently accessed files are
replicated locally, while infrequently accessed files are kept in the
cloud until requested.
